Tutorial 2 - Zod and Faker

4 steps

In this quest, you will learn Zod, a Typescript-first schema validation library, and faker, a data mocking library to produce false data for exploring and building API routes/endpoints. Once you grasp how to use zod-factory, a Typescript package that combines zod and faker, you will be ready to use the newly gained knowledge for Quest 3.

Let's continue and fire up your journey with Hono and Deno.

Prerequisites

  • Required to have finished Quest 1.
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript.
  • A working development environment of VSCode.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Required to have finished Quest 1.
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript.
  • A working development environment of VSCode.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Create mock data using faker.
  • Build type-safe schemas with zod.
  • Integrate faker and zod to your API development for testing.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: What is Zod and Faker

    Your project setup should already have been set up from Quest 1. Complete Quest 1 before heading back here.

    If you are still running the HTTP server, stop the running instance of the command by either closing the terminal or press and holding the Ctrl key then pressing c on the terminal where the deno task serve is running.

    This avoids mistakes where users are still wondering why they cannot run their server but that's just because a server is already running on the same port.

    Installing dependencies

    In this setup, you will add new dependencies, zod and zod-factory. Run the following command.

    deno add 'jsr:@findhow/zod-factory' 'npm:zod@3.23.8'

    If you are wondering where the faker dependency is, you don't need to include it since you will only have to use it already from zod-factory.

    Let's explain first what zod and faker do and then explain last on how zod-factory comes into play.

    Zod

    Zod is a Typescript-first schema validation library. It allows developers to build schemas that can be type validated. What this means is, "what you describe is what you get". Schemas in Zod can mean any data type: strings, numbers, and nested structures.

    One can then create a schema which you can infer the Typescript type. You can go further by creating nested data structures without worrying about duplicative declarations and ensuring that these data structures can be validated.

    If you want to know more about Zod, you can bookmark this link for further reading.

    Faker

    Faker is a popular Javascript library. It is used to generate mock or fake data, usually, for testing purposes and experimenting with APIs.

    It's pretty straight-forward and there really is not much to it. But one thing that faker does that makes it a good idea to use is it is easy to use and there really is no need for developers to study that hard.

    If you want to know more about faker, you can bookmark this link for further reading.

    Zod Factory

    Zod-factory is a combination between zod and faker. It's used to easily generate mock data that is also built with zod schemas. This means that developers have no need to write a boilerplate to wrap around both zod and faker. They just need to add zod-factory as a dependency and they can finally use it to generate many times of fake data in a zod schema.

    Zod-factory can be found in the JSR.

  • Step 2: Example Use Case | Pet Owner Data

    Using the same project from Quest 1, let's head to the root directory of your project. Create a new directory called mock.

    Inside the mock directory, create two new files called animal.schema.ts and factory.ts.

    Open animal.schema.ts and write the following code to animal.schema.ts.

    import { z } from "zod";

const AnimalSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string().uuid(),
  owner: z.string(),
  animal: z.string(),
});

export default AnimalSchema;
    TypeScript

    Open factory.ts and write the following code to factory.ts.

    import { factory } from "@findhow/zod-factory";
import AnimalSchema from "./animal.schema.ts";

const AnimalFactory = factory(AnimalSchema, (faker) => ({
  id: faker.string.uuid(),
  owner: faker.person.fullName(),
  animal: faker.animal.cat(),
}));

export default AnimalFactory;
    TypeScript

    You can see here that you have no need to add faker as a dependency as it's used only within the factory function from @findhow/zod-factory.

    You can see here that the schema, AnimalSchema, is used as a template schema for the factory function. faker is used in the factory function to generate mock data for the zod schema which has the following fields that match the fields in the AnimalSchema variable.

    Now, go back to the root directory of your project. Open main.ts file and replace all of its contents with the following code.

    import { Hono } from "@hono/hono";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";
import AnimalFactory from "./mock/factory.ts";

const factoryAnimals = AnimalFactory.createMany(10);

const app = new Hono().basePath("/api");

app.get("/animals", (c) => {
  return c.json(factoryAnimals);
});

app.get("/animals/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const animalDetails = factoryAnimals.find((el) => el.id === id);
  if (!animalDetails) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(animalDetails);
});

if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve({ hostname: "127.0.0.1", port: 5555 }, app.fetch);
}
    TypeScript

    Run the following command to run the server.

    deno task serve

    Perform a GET request on the following route http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/animals in Postman. Yours should look similar like the screenshot below.

    Next, choose an ID value from one of the array of JSON objects, and perform a GET request to that route with the following format http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/animals/the-id-you-chose where the-id-you-chose is the ID you chose from one of the array of JSON objects. For example, the screenshot below uses the ecf2c490-41e1-42d0-8ce1-265a6e8ad82e ID from the previous screenshot.

    Of course, it should exist, otherwise, you get a 404 status code that the ID does not exist like the screenshot below where it shows usage of a non-existent ID.

    Here is a video demo but using GitHub Codespace.

  • Step 3: Example Use Case | Personal Details Data

    The previous example is a theoretical scenario where we store Pet Owner Data. The current example you have to write is generating mock data for personal details.

    Head to the root directory of your project. Head to the mock directory. Create a file called personal-details.schema.ts. Open the file and write the following code to the new file.

    import { z } from "zod";

const PersonalDetailSchema = z.object({
  id: z.number().int(),
  firstName: z.string(),
  lastName: z.string(),
  email: z.string().email(),
  password: z.string(),
});

export default PersonalDetailSchema;
    TypeScript

    You can see here the usual fields used when a user registers. You will also notice that there is an ID, which is useful when you want to store this in a database such as an SQLite database.

    Open the file factory.ts and replace all of its contents with the following code.

    import { factory } from "@findhow/zod-factory";
import AnimalSchema from "./animal.schema.ts";
import PersonalDetailSchema from "./personal-details.schema.ts";

const AnimalFactory = factory(AnimalSchema, (faker) => ({
  id: faker.string.uuid(),
  owner: faker.person.fullName(),
  animal: faker.animal.cat(),
}));

const PersonalDetailFactory = factory(PersonalDetailSchema, (faker) => ({
  id: faker.number.int(),
  firstName: faker.person.firstName(),
  lastName: faker.person.lastName(),
  email: faker.internet.email(),
  password: faker.internet.password(),
}));

const factoryAnimals = AnimalFactory.createMany(100);
const factoryPeople = PersonalDetailFactory.createMany(100);

export { AnimalFactory, factoryAnimals, factoryPeople, PersonalDetailFactory };
    TypeScript

    Your factory.ts now has two mock data generators, each having different use cases. To test that it works, let's head back to the root directory of your project.

    Open the main.ts file and replace all of its contents with the following code.

    import { Hono } from "@hono/hono";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";
import { factoryAnimals, factoryPeople } from "./mock/factory.ts";

const animals = new Hono().basePath("/animals");
const people = new Hono().basePath("/people");
const app = new Hono().basePath("/api");

animals.get("/", (c) => {
  return c.json(factoryAnimals);
});

animals.get("/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const animalDetails = factoryAnimals.find((el) => el.id === id);
  if (!animalDetails) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(animalDetails);
});

app.route("/", animals);

people.get("/", (c) => {
  return c.json(factoryPeople);
});

people.get("/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const personalDetail = factoryPeople.find((el) =>
    el.id === Number.parseInt(id)
  );
  if (!personalDetail) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(personalDetail);
});

app.route("/", people);

if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve({ hostname: "127.0.0.1", port: 5555 }, app.fetch);
}
    TypeScript

    You should notice that the new code contains two new variables, animals and people, for the routes /animals and /people, set by the basePath method, respectively. You have discovered how to group route paths with the .route method, for example, app.route("/", animals) and app.route("/", people) without changing the base path for the app variable. Thus, all routes should start with /api.

    Let's see this in action in the video demo below.

    Here is another video demo for the people endpoint but in GitHub Codespace.

  • Step 4: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations on finishing this short tutorial. Now that you have grasped how to use zod and faker with zod-factory, you can generate mock data to test your API endpoints and API code.

    This helps you visualise how to write and manipulate data based on the API endpoints that you have created.

    Another thing to take note of is that zod, zod-factory, and faker works on multiple runtimes, so if you have a project that uses Node or Bun, you are assured that these packages work!

    Care to share interesting ideas about what kind of API you're going to build in the future? Drop a message on our Discord forum channel!
